"Brysting A.K., Gabrielsen T.M., Sørlibråten O., Ytrehorn O., Brochmann C.","The Purple Saxifrage, Saxifraga oppositifolia, ih Svalbard: Two taxa or one?",1996,"Polar Research","15","2",,"93","105",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0030326225&partnerID=40&md5=23a7d5cc038035cb08136ac063149b8f","Botanical Garden and Museum, University of Oslo, Trondheimsveien 23B, N-0562 Oslo, Norway; Department of Biology, Division of Zoology, University of Oslo, P.O. Box 1050 Blindern, N-0316 Oslo, Norway","Brysting, A.K., Botanical Garden and Museum, University of Oslo, Trondheimsveien 23B, N-0562 Oslo, Norway; Gabrielsen, T.M., Botanical Garden and Museum, University of Oslo, Trondheimsveien 23B, N-0562 Oslo, Norway; Sørlibråten, O., Department of Biology, Division of Zoology, University of Oslo, P.O. Box 1050 Blindern, N-0316 Oslo, Norway; Ytrehorn, O., Botanical Garden and Museum, University of Oslo, Trondheimsveien 23B, N-0562 Oslo, Norway; Brochmann, C., Botanical Garden and Museum, University of Oslo, Trondheimsveien 23B, N-0562 Oslo, Norway","Several studies have demonstrated high levels of genetic (DNA), ecophysiological, ecological, and morphological variation within the species Purple Saxifrage, Saxifraga oppositifolia, in Svalbard. It has recently been proposed that 5. oppositifolia is represented by two conspicuously different subspecies in this archipelago: ssp. reptans, a late-flowering, prostrate ecotype of snow-protected, damp habitats, and ssp. pulvinata, an early-flowering, cushion-like ecotype of dry, wind-exposed heaths and ridges. It has also been suggested that the subspecies may be differentiated at the tetraploid and diploid levels, respectively, which would promote reproductive isolation. These hypotheses are tested by examining variation in morphology, ecology, and pollen size and stainability in 150 plants of 5. oppositifolia growing in 50 vegetation samples at four sites in the Kongsfjorden area. Although analyses of the various data sets demonstrated the large variation within the species, the material could not be separated into distinct groups. The morphological variation was continuous along local ecological gradients. The pollen grains were fully stainable and the pollen diameter data showed a unimodal distribution, suggesting that the plants analysed represent only one ploidal level. These results reject a hypothesis that the morphologically intermediate plants are hybrids between two taxa at different ploidal levels. Thus, the conspicuous variation in S. oppositifolia in Svalbard probably results from local, in situ ecoclinal differentiation. Although this variation clearly is without taxonomic significance, it is important in the broader context of arctic conservation biology and the potential impact of global warming on arctic vegetation.",,"purple saxifrage; taxonomy; Svalbard; Saxifraga oppositifolia; Saxifragaceae",,,,,,"Abbott, R.J., Chapman, H.M., Crawford, R.M.M., Forbes, D.G., Molecular diversity and derivations of populations of Silene acaulis and Saxifraga oppositifolia from the high Arctic and more southerly latitudes (1995) Molec. Ecol., 4, pp. 199-207; Andersson, G., Hesselman, H., Bidrag til kännedomen om Spetsbergens och Beeren Eilands kärlväxtflora (1900) Bih. K. Svenska Vet.-Akad. Handl. 26, 3 (1), pp. 1-88; Bauert, M.R., Genetic diversity and ecotypic differentiation in arctic and alpine populations of Polygonum viviparum (1996) Arct. Alp. Res., 28, pp. 190-195; Braak, C.J.F., (1987) CANOCO - A FORTRAN Program for Canonical Community Ordination by (Partial)(detrended)(canonical) Correspondence Analysis, Principal Components Analysis and Redundancy Analysis (Version 2.1), , TNO Inst. appl. Comp. Sci., Stat. Dept. Wageningen, Wageningen; Brattbakk, I., (1981) Brøggerhalvøya, Svalbard. Vegetasjonskart 1:10.000, , K. Norske Vitensk. Selsk. Mus. Bot. Avd., Trondheim; Brochmann, C., Evaluation of some methods for hybrid analysis, exemplified by hybridization in Argyranthemum